rug", "prob": 0.835873007774353, "span": {"begin": 632, "end": 642}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:54145"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "histones", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9612576365470886, "span": {"begin": 655, "end": 663}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:9734"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "HDAC", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9492035508155823, "span": {"begin": 665, "end": 669}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:54145"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "histones", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.991025984287262, "span": {"begin": 742, "end": 750}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:8337"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "H2A", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.993235170841217, "span": {"begin": 767, "end": 770}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:8349"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "H2B", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9927767515182495, "span": {"begin": 772, "end": 775}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:126961", "117579"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "H3", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 777, "end": 779}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:59340", "8370", "8030", "8361"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "H4", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 785, "end": 787}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:9734"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "HDACs", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9428972601890564, "span": {"begin": 843, "end": 848}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7275"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "tubulin", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9864895343780518, "span": {"begin": 907, "end": 914}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:54145"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "histones", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9847211241722107, "span": {"begin": 918, "end": 926}}], "text": "Gene transcription is regulated with the balance between acetylation and deacetylation. A dynamic balance of histone acetylation and histone deacetylation is typically catalyzed by enzymes with histone acetyltransferase (HAT) and HDAC activities. Histone acetylation relaxes chromatin and makes it accessible to transcription factors, whereas deacetylation is associated with gene silencing. The balance can be disturbed also by targeting HAT, not only HDACs. At least theoretically, an activation of HAT might lead to an increase in histone acetylation. The acetylation and deacetylation are modulated on the NH3+ groups of lysine amino acid residues in histones. HDAC inhibition promotes hyperacetylation by inhibiting the deacetylation of histones with classes of H2A, H2B, H3, and H4 in nucleosomes. [Wade et al., 2008]. The inhibition of HDACs results in an accumulation of acetylated proteins such as tubulin or histones.", "timestamp": "Fri May 15 21:41:59 +0000 2026"}